# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: artificial-insemination
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] The general risks of ultrasound also apply to 3D ultrasound.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Essentially, ultrasound is considered safe.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] While other imaging modalities use radioactive dye or ionizing radiation, for example, ultrasound transducers send pulses of high frequency sound into the body and then listen for the echo.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] In summary, the primary risks associated with ultrasound would be the potential heating of tissue or cavitation.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] The mechanisms by which tissue heating and cavitation are measured are through the standards called thermal index (TI) and mechanical index (MI).
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Even though the FDA outlines very safe values for maximum TI and MI, it is still recommended to avoid unnecessary ultrasound imaging.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] 3D ultrasound is useful, among other things, for facilitating the characterization of some congenital defects, such as skeletal anomalies and heart issues.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] With real-time 3D ultrasound, the fetal heart rate can be examined in real-time.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Applications of three-dimensional ultrasound in cardiac treatment have achieved outstanding progress in scanning and treating heart issues.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] When 3D ultrasound is used to visualize the cardiac state of an individual, it is called 3D echocardiography.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] With the integration of other technologies, it is possible to obtain quantitative measurements such as chamber volume during the cardiac cycle.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] It also provides other useful information, for example, tracking the blood flow, or the speed of contractions and expansions.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] With 3D echocardiography, physicians can detect artery diseases with relative ease, and can finely examine various cardiac defects.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] 3D echocardiography can achieve real-time imaging of the cardiac structure.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Traditionally, with 2D ultrasound, the specific position of organs and tissues, which is useful in surgery, could not be located, especially in the oblique plane.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] With the advent of 3D ultrasound, the imaging technique has evolved such that it enables the surgeon to obtain a real-time picture of tissues and organs, visualizing the complete scan more efficiently.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] In addition, 3D ultrasound provides surgical guidance in organ transplantation and cancer treatment, especially by employing rotational visualizing during scan.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Various methods are used in this area, including rotational scanning, slice projection, and the use of integrated array transducers.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] With 3D ultrasound, it is possible to treat a broader range of tumors, as more tissues can be diagnosed and inspected.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Blood vessels and arteries are relatively difficult to image, due to their distribution.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] 3D ultrasound has made it easier to track the dynamic movement of blood cells, veins and arteries.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Various types of diagnostic tasks can be achieved with 3D ultrasound, such as measuring blood vessel diameter and diagnosing arterial walls.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Some of these tasks can be undertaken with a magnetic tracker, integrated with the ultrasound, which assists in accurate positioning.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Real-time 3D ultrasound is used during peripheral nerve blockade procedures to identify the relevant anatomy and monitor the spread of local anesthetic around the nerve.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Peripheral nerve blockades prevent the transmission of pain signals from the site of injury to the brain without deep sedation, which makes them particularly useful for outpatient orthopedic procedures.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Real-time 3D ultrasound allows muscles, nerves and vessels to be clearly identified while a needle or catheter is advanced under the skin.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] This type of ultrasound is capable of imaging the needle regardless of the plane of the image, which is a substantial improvement over 2D ultrasound.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Additionally, the image can be rotated or cropped in real time to reveal anatomical structures within a volume of tissue.
[src:artificial-insemination/3d-ultrasound] Physicians at the Mayo Clinic in Jacksonville have been developing techniques using real time 3D ultrasound to guide peripheral nerve blocks for shoulder, knee, and ankle surgery.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] An **abdominal pregnancy** is a rare type of ectopic pregnancy where the embryo or fetus is growing and developing outside the uterus, in the abdomen, and not in a fallopian tube (usual location), an ovary, or the broad ligament.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Because tubal, ovarian and broad ligament pregnancies are as difficult to diagnose and treat as abdominal pregnancies, their exclusion from the most common definition of abdominal pregnancy has been debated.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Others—in the minority—are of the view that abdominal pregnancy should be defined by a placenta implanted into the peritoneum.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Symptoms may include abdominal pain or vaginal bleeding during pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] As this is nonspecific in areas where ultrasound is not available the diagnosis was often only discovered during surgery to investigate the abnormal symptoms.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] They are typically diagnosed later in the developing world than the developed.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] In about half of cases from a center in the developing world the diagnosis was initially missed.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] It is a dangerous condition as there can be bleeding into the abdomen that results in low blood pressure and can be fatal.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Other causes of death in women with an abdominal pregnancy include anemia, pulmonary embolus, coagulopathy, and infection.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Implantation sites can be anywhere in the abdomen but can include the peritoneum outside of the uterus, the rectouterine pouch (culdesac of Douglas), omentum, bowel and its mesentery, mesosalpinx, and the peritoneum of the pelvic wall and the abdominal wall.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] The growing placenta may be attached to several organs including tube and ovary.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Rare other sites have been the liver and spleen, giving rise to a hepatic pregnancy or splenic pregnancy, respectively.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Even an early diaphragmatic pregnancy has been described in a patient where an embryo began growing on the underside of the diaphragm.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] A primary abdominal pregnancy refers to a pregnancy that first implanted directly in the peritoneum, save for the tubes and ovaries; such pregnancies are very rare, only 24 cases having been reported by 2007.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Typically an abdominal pregnancy is a secondary implantation which means that it originated from a tubal (less common an ovarian) pregnancy and re-implanted.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Other mechanisms for secondary abdominal pregnancy include uterine rupture, rupture of a uterine rudimentary horn and fimbrial abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Suspicion of an abdominal pregnancy is raised when the fetal anatomy can be easily felt, or the lie is abnormal, the cervix is displaced, or there is failed induction of labor.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] MRI has also been used with success to diagnose abdominal pregnancy and plan for surgery.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Elevated alpha-fetoprotein levels are another clue of the presence of an abdominal pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Most cases can be diagnosed by ultrasound.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] The diagnosis however may be missed with ultrasound depending on the operator's skill.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Studdiford's criteria were refined in 1968 by Friedrich and Rankin to include microscopic findings.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Depending on gestational age the differential diagnoses for abdominal pregnancy include miscarriage, intrauterine fetal death, placental abruption, an acute abdomen with an intrauterine pregnancy and a fibroid uterus with an intrauterine pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Ideally the management of abdominal pregnancy should be done by a team that has medical personnel from multiple specialties.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Potential treatments consist of surgery with termination of the pregnancy (removal of the fetus) via laparoscopy or laparotomy, use of methotrexate, embolization, and combinations of these.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] The choice is largely dictated by the clinical situation.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Generally, treatment is indicated when the diagnosis is made; however, the situation of the advanced abdominal pregnancy is more complicated.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Advanced abdominal pregnancy refers to situations where the pregnancy continues past 20 weeks of gestation (versus early abdominal pregnancy < 20 weeks).
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] In those situations, live births have been reported in the lay press where the babies are not uncommonly referred to as 'miracle babies'.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] A patient may carry a dead fetus but will not go into labor.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Over time, the fetus calcifies and becomes a lithopedion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] It is generally recommended to perform a laparotomy when the diagnosis of an abdominal pregnancy is made.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] However, if the baby is alive and medical support systems are in place, careful watching could be considered to bring the baby to viability.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Women with an abdominal pregnancy will not go into labor.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Delivery in a case of an advanced abdominal pregnancy will have to be via laparotomy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] The survival of the baby is reduced and high perinatal mortality rates between 40% and 95% have been reported.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Babies of abdominal pregnancies are prone to birth defects due to compression in the absence of the uterine wall and the often reduced amount of amniotic fluid surrounding the unborn baby.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] The rate of malformations and deformations is estimated to be about 21%; typical deformations are facial and cranial asymmetries and joint abnormalities and the most common malformations are limb defects and central nervous malformations.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Once the baby has been delivered placental management becomes an issue.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] In normal deliveries the contraction of uterus provides a powerful mechanism to control blood loss, however, in an abdominal pregnancy the placenta is located over tissue that cannot contract and attempts of its removal may lead to life-threatening blood loss.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Thus blood transfusion is frequent in the management of patients with this kind of pregnancy, with others even using tranexamic acid and recombinant factor VIIa, which both minimize blood loss.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Generally, unless the placenta can be easily tied off or removed, it may be preferable to leave it in place and allow for a natural regression.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] This process may take several months and can be monitored by clinical examination, checking human chorionic gonadotropin levels and by ultrasound scanning (in particular using doppler ultrasonography.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Use of methotrexate to accelerate placental regression is controversial as the large amount of necrotic tissue is a potential site for infection, mifepristone has also been used to promote placental regression.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Placental vessels have also been blocked by angiographic embolization.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Complications of leaving the placenta can include residual bleeding, infection, bowel obstruction, pre-eclampsia (which may all necessitate further surgery) and failure to breast feed due to placental hormones.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Outcome with abdominal pregnancy can be good for the baby and mother; Lampe described an abdominal pregnancy baby and her mother who were well more than 22 years after surgery.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] About 1.4% of ectopic pregnancies are abdominal, or about 1 out of every 8,000 pregnancies.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] A report from Nigeria places the frequency in that country at 34 per 100,000 deliveries and a report from Zimbabwe, 11 per 100,000 deliveries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] The maternal mortality rate is estimated to be about 5 per 1,000 cases, about seven times the rate for ectopics in general, and about 90 times the rate for a "normal" delivery (1987 US data).
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Because pregnancy is outside the uterus, abdominal pregnancy serves as a model of human male pregnancy or for females who lack a uterus, although such pregnancy would be dangerous.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Abdominal pregnancy has served to further clarify the disease pre-eclampsia which was previously thought (1980s) to require a uterus for it to occur, however pre-eclampsia's occurrence in abdominal pregnancy (with the conceptus outside the uterus) helped throw light on pre-eclampsia's etiology.
[src:artificial-insemination/abdominal-pregnancy] Cases of combined simultaneous abdominal and intrauterine pregnancy have been reported.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:artificial-insemination/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] The laws of many jurisdictions void incestuous marriages, even if entered into without awareness of the kinship.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] If an incestuous relationship is suspected, DNA testing may be used.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] Some jurisdictions permit offspring of IVF donations access to donation records or to adoption records.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] People may be unaware of a kinship relationship between them in a number of circumstances.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] For example, artificial insemination with an anonymous donated sperm may result in offspring being unaware of any biological relations, such as paternity or half siblings.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] To reduce the likelihood of accidental incest, fertility clinics usually limit the number of times that a donor's sperm may be used.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] Some countries have laws limiting the number of children a donor can father, while others limit sperm donations based on family numbers to enable one family to have true siblings.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] Taiwan allows those conceived by artificial means to find out if they are related to a person they are considering marrying.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] Genetic sexual attraction is an unproven hypothesis, commonly considered pseudoscience, offered as an explanation for cases of sexual attraction and relations between adults who were not aware of their close blood relations.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] In 2008, during a debate on the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 2008 in the House of Lords, Lord Alton of Liverpool claimed that a British brother and sister, who were twins separated at birth, married without knowing of their relationship.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] According to Lord Alton, the relationship was discovered soon after their wedding, and the marriage was annulled.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] The case was raised regarding whether adoptions should be kept secret.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] Questions were raised about whether the story is actually true, as Lord Alton was known to oppose the act due to its provision allowing the creation and use of animal-human hybrid stem cells for medical purposes.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] An engaged couple in South Africa, who had been together for five years and were expecting a child, discovered that they were brother and sister just before their wedding.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] They were raised separately and met as adults in college.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] Just before the wedding, their parents met and they came to realize that they were siblings.
[src:artificial-insemination/accidental-incest] The couple broke off the relationship after the discovery.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Acute fatty liver of pregnancy (or hepatic lipidosis of pregnancy) usually manifests in the third trimester of pregnancy, but may occur any time in the second half of pregnancy, or the puerperium, the period immediately after delivery.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] On average, the disease presents during the 35th or 36th week of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] In patients with more severe disease, pre-eclampsia may occur, which involves elevation of blood pressure and accumulation of fluid (termed oedema).
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] This may progress to involvement of additional systems, including acute kidney failure, hepatic encephalopathy, and pancreatitis.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] There have also been reports of diabetes insipidus complicating this condition.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Many laboratory abnormalities are seen in acute fatty liver of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Liver enzymes are elevated, with the AST and ALT enzymes ranging from minimal elevation to 1000 IU/L, but usually staying in the 300-500 range.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Bilirubin is almost universally elevated.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Alkaline phosphatase is often elevated in pregnancy due to production from the placenta, but may be additionally elevated.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Other abnormalities may include an elevated white blood cell count, hypoglycemia, elevated coagulation parameters, including the international normalized ratio, and decreased fibrinogen.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Frank disseminated intravascular coagulation, or DIC, may occur in as many as 70% of people.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Abdominal ultrasound may show fat deposition in the liver, but, as the hallmark of this condition is microvesicular steatosis (see pathology below), this is not seen on ultrasound.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Rarely, the condition can be complicated by rupture or necrosis of the liver, which may be identified by ultrasound.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The understanding of the causes of acute fatty liver of pregnancy has been improved by advances in mitochondrial biochemistry.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Deficiency of LCHAD (3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase) leads to an accumulation of medium and long chain fatty acids.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] When this occurs in the foetus, the unmetabolized fatty acids will re-enter the maternal circulation through the placenta, and overwhelm the beta-oxidation enzymes of the mother.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The gene responsible for LCHAD has been isolated, and the most common mutation found in acute fatty liver of pregnancy is the E474Q missense mutation.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] LCHAD deficiency is autosomal recessive in inheritance and mothers are often found to be heterozygous for the affected mutation.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The diagnosis of acute fatty liver of pregnancy is usually made on clinical grounds by the treating physician, but differentiation from other conditions affecting the liver may be difficult.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The diagnosis of acute fatty liver of pregnancy is suggested by jaundice with a lesser elevation of liver enzymes, elevated white blood cell count, disseminated intravascular coagulation, and a clinically unwell patient.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] A liver biopsy can provide a definitive diagnosis, but is not always done, due to the increased chance of bleeding in acute fatty liver of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Often testing will be done to exclude more common conditions that present similarly, including viral hepatitis, pre-eclampsia, HELLP syndrome, intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy, and autoimmune hepatitis.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] If a liver biopsy is needed for diagnosis of the condition, the mother should be appropriately stabilized and treated to reduce bleeding-related complications.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The diagnosis can be made by a frozen section (as opposed to a specimen in formalin) that is stained with the **Oil red O** stain, which shows microvesicular steatosis (or small collections of fat within the liver cells).
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The microvesicular steatosis usually spares zone one of the liver, which is the area closest to the hepatic artery.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] On the regular trichrome stain, the liver cell cytoplasm shows a foamy appearance due to the prominence of fat.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The diagnosis can be enhanced by electron microscopy, which can be used to confirm the presence of microvesicular steatosis, and specifically the presence of megamitochondria and paracrystalline inclusions.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Acute fatty liver of pregnancy is best treated in a centre with expertise in hepatology, high-risk obstetrics, maternal-fetal medicine, and neonatology.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Physicians who treat this condition will often consult with experts in liver transplantation in severe cases.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Admission to the intensive care unit is recommended.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Initial treatment involves supportive management with intravenous fluids, intravenous glucose, and blood products, including fresh frozen plasma and cryoprecipitate to correct DIC.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The foetus should be monitored with cardiotocography.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] After the mother is stabilized, arrangements are usually made for delivery.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] This may occur vaginally, but, in cases of severe bleeding or compromise of the mother's status, a caesarian section may be needed.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Often, AFLP is not diagnosed until the mother and baby are in trouble, so it is most likely that an emergency C-section is needed.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The complications of acute fatty liver of pregnancy may require treatment after delivery, especially if pancreatitis occurs.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Liver transplantation is rarely required for treatment of the condition, but may be needed for mothers with severe DIC, those with rupture of the liver, or those with severe encephalopathy.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Acute fatty liver of pregnancy is a rare condition and occurs in approximately one in 7,000 to one in 15,000 pregnancies.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The mortality from acute fatty liver of pregnancy has been reduced significantly to 18% and is now related primarily to complications, particularly DIC (Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation) and infections.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] After delivery, most mothers do well, as the stimulus for fatty acid overload is removed.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The disease can recur in future pregnancies, with a calculated genetic chance of 25%; the actual rate is lower, however.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Mortality of the foetus has also diminished significantly, but remains 23%, and may be related to the need for premature delivery.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] The disease was first described in 1940 by H.
[src:artificial-insemination/acute-fatty-liver-of-pregnancy] Sheehan as an "acute yellow atrophy" of the liver, then thought to be related to delayed chloroform poisoning.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] At the end of pregnancy, the fetus must take the journey of childbirth to leave the reproductive mother.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Upon its entry to the air-breathing world, the newborn must begin to adjust to life outside the uterus.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] This is true for all viviparous animals; this article discusses humans as the most-researched example.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The outside environment is a drastic change for the neonate; therefore, the neonate must be assessed frequently and thoroughly.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The Apgar scale is an assessment performed immediately following birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] It consists of assessing heart rate, respiratory effort, muscle tone, reflex irritability, and overall skin color.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Apgar scoring is performed one minute and five minutes after birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Scoring ranges from 0 to 10, with 0 indicating severe neonatal distress and 10 indicating a smooth transition to extrauterine life.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Newborns transitioning into extrauterine life will undergo periods of reactivity.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] These periods are divided into three stages.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The first stage occurs in the first 30 minutes of life; during this stage, the infant is alert and responsive with heart rate peaking at 160–180 beats per minute and then stabilizes to a baseline rate of 100–120 beats per minute.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Crackles upon auscultation and irregular respirations are a normal finding.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] In the second stage, there is a decrease in responsiveness and motor activity, often manifesting as sleep.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The third stage marks the second period of reactivity.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] This period can occur anywhere from 2 to 8 hours after birth and lasts from 10 minutes to several hours.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Tachycardia and tachypnea may be present during brief periods.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] In utero, the placenta delivers oxygenated blood to the fetus through the umbilical vein.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Upon delivery, the umbilical cord is cut.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The cardiovascular system must now adapt.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Blood CO2 rises because it is now not removed by the placenta.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] This is a powerful stimulus for the infant to start breathing.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Breathing sharply increases O2 in the lungs, thus quickly reverting hypoxic pulmonary vasoconstriction that had held the pulmonary vascular resistance high during the uterine life.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Lung ventilation also extends the so far convoluted, shrunk pulmonary vessels, also contributing to the quick and marked drop in the pulmonary vascular resistance.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] As a result, a much higher proportion of the right ventricle output flows into the pulmonary vessels than into the systemic circulation through the ductus arteriosus.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The detachment of the placenta causes an increase in systemic vascular resistance, which leads to an increase in pressure gradient from the left atrium.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The left atrium now has higher pressure than the right atrium, causing the foramen ovale to close.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Within the first 10 minutes of birth, blood begins to flow left-to-right through the ductus arteriosus.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] This causes a significant increase in the output of the left ventricle and an increase in stroke volume.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Subsequently, calcium channel activity increases and potassium channel decreases, furthering ductal constriction.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Functional closure of the ductus arteriosus occurs within the first 24 hours, with permanent closure following within 4 weeks.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Lastly, cardiac output increases to nearly double what it was in utero.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] All of these cardiovascular system changes result in the adaptation from fetal circulation patterns to an adult circulation pattern.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] During this transition, some types of congenital heart disease that were not symptomatic *in utero* during fetal circulation will present with cyanosis or respiratory signs.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] When the newborn cries, there is a reversal of blood flow through the foramen ovale, which causes the newborn to appear mildly cyanotic in the first few days of life.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The heart rate of the newborn should be between 110 and 160 beats per minute, and it is common for the heart rate to be irregular in the first few hours following birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The heart sounds will have a variation in pitch, duration, and intensity than that of an adult.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Blood pressure readings should range from 60 to 80 mm Hg systolic and 40–50 mm Hg diastolic.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Mean arterial pressure should be the same as the weeks of gestation at birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Within the first hour after birth, there may be a drop of up to 15 mm Hg in the systolic blood pressure.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Delayed cord clamping is defined as waiting more than 2 minutes to clamp the newborn's umbilical cord.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] This has been proven to be beneficial in improving hematocrit and iron while also decreasing anemia.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] These benefits can last up to 6 months for the newborn.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Assessment and monitoring of vital signs and skin color are important in detecting cardiovascular issues in the infant.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The apical pulse rate should be auscultated for one full minute when the newborn is calm or sleeping.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Any irregular heart rate after the first few hours of life that is not related to crying or another outside factor should be monitored and evaluated.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Blood pressure will be taken with an appropriately sized cuff, preferably when the newborn is at rest.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Consistent tachycardia should be evaluated for conditions such as anemia, hyperthermia, hypovolemia, and sepsis.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Consistent bradycardia could be an indication of congenital heart block or hypoxemia.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Pallor and central cyanosis (cyanosis in hands and feet is a common and normal finding) can also indicate cardiovascular issues.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Upon birth, the newborn's lungs become the center for gas exchange.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] There are a variety of factors that influence newborn respiratory functions; these factors include chemical, mechanical, thermal, and sensory.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Respirations begin when fetal aortic and carotid chemoreceptors are stimulated by the varying concentrations of oxygen and carbon dioxide.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] During vaginal birth, the newborn's chest is compressed by the birth canal.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Upon delivery, negative pressure allows air into the lungs.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The first cries of the infant allow for alveoli expansion and absorption of fetal lung fluid.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Temperature changes and other sensory stimulation contribute to respiratory function as well.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Breathing patterns are often irregular and shallow.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The infant's respiration rate should be between 30 and 60 breaths per minute, with a preference for nasal breathing.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Breath sounds should be clear and equal in both lungs.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Suctioning of nasal and oral secretions promotes fluid clearance.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Auscultation of lung sounds to assess for any abnormalities.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Pulse oximetry is performed to determine oxygen saturation.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Monitor signs of respiratory distress such as: nasal flaring, grunting, central cyanosis.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] At birth, the newborn is cut off from the mother's glucose supply and will begin to rely on stored fat for energy.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Within the first hour of life, blood glucose will typically reach its lowest point and then stabilize within 2 to 4 hours; hence breastfeeding is promoted immediately.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] In cases where feeding is delayed, the neonate can use lactate, free-fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Normal blood glucose levels range from 40 to 50 mg/dl.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Rooting and sucking reflexes should be present, and the neonate will eat small amounts frequently.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] All vital signs should be within normal limits, coinciding with the neonate's presentation of calmness and satiation.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Monitor blood glucose level and encourage breastfeeding or formula feeding as early as possible.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Lactation and breastfeeding education should be provided as appropriate.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Newborns lack the ability for thermogenesis due to an underdeveloped shivering mechanism.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Body heat is lost through conduction, convection, and radiant heat.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Thermoregulation is achieved through several methods: the metabolism of brown fat and Kangaroo care, also known as skin-to-skin.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] "Brown fat" is specialized adipose tissue with a high concentration of mitochondria designed to rapidly oxidize fatty acids to generate metabolic heat.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Skin to skin to care is the immediate placement of the neonate directly onto a caregiver's bare chest.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] This promotes thermoregulation of the neonate through heat generated by the caregiver.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Cold infants may cry or appear restless.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] The neonates' arms and legs maintain a fetal position, lessening their body surface area and reducing heat loss.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Dry the neonate immediately after birth and initiate skin-to-skin contact.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Utilize a radiant warmer if skin-to-skin is not appropriate.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Frequently monitor axillary body temperature.
[src:artificial-insemination/adaptation-to-extrauterine-life] Limit the neonate's exposure during diaper changes and assessments.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The **American Quarter Horse Association** (**AQHA**), based in Amarillo, Texas, United States, is an international organization dedicated to the preservation, improvement and record-keeping of the American Quarter Horse.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The association sanctions many competitive events and maintains the official registry.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The organization also houses the American Quarter Horse Hall of Fame and Museum and sponsors educational programs.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The organization was founded in 1940 in Fort Worth, Texas, and now has nearly 234,627 members, over 32,000 of whom are international.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The American Quarter Horse Association was born at a meeting on March 15, 1940, in Fort Worth, Texas.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The original idea had come from articles published by Robert M.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Denhardt during the 1930s about the history and characteristics of the quarter horse.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] In an article entitled "The Quarter Horse, Then and Now" in a 1939 *Western Horseman* magazine, Denhardt also suggested that those interested in forming a breed registry meet in Fort Worth to discuss the idea and hopefully act on the idea.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] About seventy-five people met in Fort Worth to discuss the proposals, with the eventual decision being to form a non-profit stock holding association in Texas to be the registry.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Thirty-six people bought stock at the initial meeting.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] A board of directors and officers were selected.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] For the first five years, AQHA was the only registry for American Quarter Horses, however there were controversies over which horses would be registered, as well as how much non-Quarter horse to allow in.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Other disputes included the fact that AQHA only allowed stock owners to vote, and some breeders felt that this arrangement kept too much power in too few hands.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Another contentious issue was racing, and how the association would support the needs of breeders and owners who raced their Quarter Horses.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] All three of these issues were woven together, for the racing interests were also desirous of more Thoroughbred blood being added to the Quarter Horse, and some racing breeders felt that the AQHA was too restrictive on what outside blood was allowed in.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The racing interests formed the American Quarter Racing Association (AQRA) on February 1, 1945.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] This group mainly was concerned with the operation of racetracks and their registration efforts were limited to what was needed for identification for racing purposes.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] They set the standards for racing, and set up a Register of Merit system to help with handicapping racing.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] They registered horses that were in AQHA's stud books, as well as Thoroughbreds.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Even "Paint" horses, which at this time had no registry and would not for another two decades, were registered.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Painted Joe, a foundation stallion with the American Paint Horse Association (APHA), was registered with the AQRA and ran against many of the early Quarter Horse racers.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Individuals who believed AQHA was too restrictive in its registration and membership policies formed the National Quarter Horse Breeders Association (NQHBA) in December 1945.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Registration criteria in the NQHBA were much less stringent than AQHA, but yet were not exclusively focused on racing like AQRA.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] For example, Thoroughbred crosses were freely registrable in NQHBA, and they even registered Thoroughbreds.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Within AQHA, there was a recognition that three organizations were sapping the strengths of the Quarter Horse breeders and owners, and within all three organizations there were efforts to merge.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] In July 1949, AQHA offered to merge with both AQRA and NQHBA.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The AQRA voted to merge with AQHA in September 1949, and the NQHBA did likewise in November 1949.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] AQHA absorbed both organizations and moved their records to AQHA's recently established headquarters off Interstate 40 in Amarillo.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] According to an article in the Amarillo Globe Times, the AQHA was based in College Station, Eagle Pass and Fort Worth before moving to Amarillo (home of the secretary Raymond D.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Hollingsworth) in 1947, where they rented space at 1405 B W.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Their first owned building was constructed in 1952 at 2736 W.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] 10th Avenue where they remained until construction of the Hall of Fame off Interstate 40 in 1989.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] AQHA now registers the offspring of other American Quarter Horses in its numbered stud book.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] However, AQHA does not maintain a completely closed stud book; there is also an "Appendix" section.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] An "Appendix" American Quarter Horse is a first generation cross between a registered Thoroughbred and an American Quarter Horse or a cross between a "numbered" American Quarter Horse and an "appendix" American Quarter Horse.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Horses in the "appendix" registry can "earn" their way into the main stud book by completing an extensive set of performance requirements in either racing or some form of show competition and receiving what the Association refers to as a Register of Merit (ROM).
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Currently there are over 2,800,000 Quarter Horse registrations, 430,000 of which are international.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Horses produced by means of artificial insemination or embryo transfer may be registered, but cloned horses cannot be registered.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Parentage now is verified by means of DNA testing.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] In recent years, registration requirements for AQHA have significantly changed.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] In the past, horses with too much white or with cremello traits were not eligible for registration.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] There was also belief that excess white indicated "impure" breeding with non-Quarter Horses.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Today, modern DNA testing has now made verification of parentage possible, and also permits the detection of certain genetic diseases such as lethal white syndrome.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Thus AQHA now allows registration of "high white" body markings typical of the sabino gene and other pinto spotting patterns.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Many horses formerly registrable only as American Paint Horses with APHA are now cross-registered with both registries.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Because the genetic mechanism that creates palomino is also understood and has been found to have no connection to lethal white, cremello and perlino coat colors are also allowed.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Cross-registration of American Quarter Horses with APHA, the Palomino Horse Breeders of America (PHBA), and the American Buckskin Registry Association (ABRA), is often a benefit to horses who have these distinct colors.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Currently, AQHA is in the process of phasing out registration of horses who carry the dominant genetic disease hyperkalemic periodic paralysis (HYPP) and sponsored research that, in 2007, developed a genetic test for HERDA.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Currently AQHA recognizes achievement by American Quarter Horses and their owners with a number of awards.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Some are annual, some are based on lifetime achievement.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] AQHA awards points to horses competing in horse show, rodeo and horse racing.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] AQHA assigns points to animals who win or place in horse shows and on the racetrack.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The number of points given depends in part on placing and on how many other horses were in the class or race.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Accumulated points result in annual awards to the top competitors and certain lifetime achievement recognitions for both horse and rider.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] As of 2023, AQHA has affiliate associations in 49 US states, 7 Canadian provinces, and 34 other countries.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Driving classes are available at some shows, as are some timed games.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] There are also equitation and halter showmanship classes for non-pro exhibitors.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The annual AQHA World Show, the largest AQHA-sponsored event, is held in November of each year in Oklahoma City.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] As lifetime awards, the AQHA awards Register of Merits in Performance and Halter, AQHA Champion, AQHA Performance Champion, AQHA Versatility Champion, Superior Event Horse, Supreme Championships in the three showing divisions (Youth, Open, Amateur), and a Supreme Performance Champion.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Requirements can change, these are the current requirements as of January 2010.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] AQHA also recognizes horses that compete outside of AQHA sanctioned shows.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] On the racetrack, AQHA offers year-end champion awards in age and sex divisions, plus broodmare, distance horse, Canadian champion, owner, breeder, trainer, and jockey.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Thus there is a champion two-year-old colt, filly and gelding plus champion two-year-old from the preceding.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The three-year-old and aged categories work the same way, with the World Champion being chosen from the winners of the age and sex divisions.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] In addition to the year end awards, there are three lifetime awards - Race Register of Merit, Superior Race Horse and Supreme Race Horse.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] A Register of Merit is awarded when a horse attains a speed index of 80 or above.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] A Superior Race Horse is achieved when the horse earns 200 racing points.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] A Supreme Race Horse award requires the horse to satisfy the following three criteria: (1) win over $500,000 in earnings, (2) win two Grade 1 stakes races and (3) win a total of ten races.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] In 1993, AQHA launched Quarter Horse racing's first series of races with a championship-ending day, called The Bank of America Racing Challenge.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] It is a series of 60 races run throughout North and South America with the winners of each race earning a starting berth into a season-ending Championship Day.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The Bank of America Racing Challenge currently offers nearly $6 million in purse and bonus awards.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] AQHA also offers a Horseback Riding Program, which rewards AQHA members for pleasure riding of American Quarter Horses.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] Riders log their hours spent riding, and receive recognition awards and prizes.
[src:artificial-insemination/aqha] The horse must be registered with the AQHA and his number an registration name will be needed to peripatetic.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination may employ assisted reproductive technology, sperm donation and animal husbandry techniques.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination techniques available include intracervical insemination (**ICI**) and intrauterine insemination (**IUI**).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Where gametes from a third party are used, the procedure may be known as '**assisted insemination**'.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The first recorded case of artificial insemination was by Lazzaro Spallanzani in 1784, who performed it on a dog.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It was followed in 1790 by John Hunter, who helped impregnate a linen draper's wife.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The first reported case of artificial insemination by donor occurred in 1884: William H.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Pancoast, a professor in Philadelphia, took sperm from his "best looking" student to inseminate an anesthetized woman without her knowledge.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The case was reported 25 years later in a medical journal.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The sperm bank was developed in Iowa starting in the 1950s in research conducted by University of Iowa medical school researchers Jerome K.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In 1916, Australian eugenicist Marion Louisa Piddington published a pseudonymous tract titled *Via Nuova or Science & Maternity* in which she called for a programme of mass artificial insemination for the sweethearts of soldiers who had been killed in World War I.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] She described this as a "conscription of the virgins" – comparable to the conscription of men for military service – who would receive "artificial insemination from a eugenically-desirable donor".
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Piddington promoted her scheme for several years in Australia, Britain and the United States under the name of "scientific motherhood", but it was poorly received.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In the United Kingdom, British obstetrician Mary Barton founded one of the first fertility clinics to offer donor insemination in the 1930s, with her husband Bertold Wiesner fathering hundreds of offspring.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination (AI) is a medical procedure in which sperm is introduced into a woman's reproductive system to achieve pregnancy without sexual intercourse.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The sperm used may come from the recipient's partner or from a donor, whose identity may be known or anonymous.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Various methods exist to obtain sperm for use in artificial insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In 2016, an article was published in Seventeen magazine that highlighted the story of Kacie Saxer-Taulbee, a teenager conceived from a sperm donor father.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Using her donor's cryobank number in the Donor Sibling Registry, she managed to find other siblings conceived from the same donor.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] They became known as the "5010ers" and formed a Facebook group to keep in touch.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Some countries have laws which restrict and regulate who can donate sperm and who is able to receive artificial insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Timing is critical, as the window and opportunity for fertilization is little more than twelve hours from the release of the ovum.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] To increase the chance of success, the woman's menstrual cycle is closely observed, often using ovulation kits, ultrasounds or blood tests, such as basal body temperature tests over, noting the color and texture of the vaginal mucus, and the softness of the nose of her cervix.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] To improve the success rate of artificial insemination, drugs to create a stimulated cycle may be used, but the use of such drugs also results in an increased chance of a multiple birth.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Semen used is either fresh, raw, or frozen.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Intracervical insemination (ICI) is the method of artificial insemination which most closely mimics the natural ejaculation of semen by the penis into the vagina during sexual intercourse.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It is painless and is the simplest and most common method of artificial insemination involving the introduction of unwashed or raw semen into the vagina at the entrance to the cervix, usually by means of a needle-less syringe.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The vagina acts as a filter to separate out the sperm from other chemicals in the ejaculate, as with intercourse, so that only sperm pass through the cervix on their way to the uterus.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Although ICI is the simplest method of artificial insemination, a meta-analysis has shown no difference in live birth rates compared with IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] During ICI, air is expelled from a needleless syringe which is then filled with semen which has been allowed to liquify.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A specially designed syringe, wider and with a more rounded end, may be used for this purpose.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Any further enclosed air is removed by gently pressing the plunger forward.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The woman lies on her back and the syringe is inserted into the vagina.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Care is optimal when inserting the syringe, so that the tip is as close to the entrance to the cervix as possible.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A vaginal speculum may be used for this purpose and a catheter may be attached to the tip of the syringe to ensure delivery of the semen as close to the entrance to the cervix as possible.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The plunger is then slowly pushed forward and the semen in the syringe is gently emptied deep into the vagina.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It is important that the syringe is emptied slowly for safety and for the best results, bearing in mind that the purpose of the procedure is to replicate as closely as possible a natural deposit of the semen in the vagina.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The syringe (and catheter if used) may be left in place for several minutes before removal.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The woman can bring herself to orgasm so that the cervix 'dips down' into the pool of semen, again replicating closely vaginal intercourse, and this may improve the success rate.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] When performed at home without the presence of a professional, aiming the sperm in the vagina at the neck of the cervix may be more difficult to achieve and the effect may be to 'flood' the vagina with semen, rather than to target it specifically at the entrance to the cervix.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] This procedure is sometimes referred to as '**intravaginal insemination'** (IVI).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Intrauterine insemination (IUI) involves injection of 'washed' sperm directly into the uterus with a catheter.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Washing involves the removal of chemicals other than sperm which are in the natural ejaculate.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In forms of vaginal insemination, including artificial vaginal insemination and ICI, these chemicals will be filtered out by the vagina.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Insemination in this way also means that the sperm do not have to swim through the cervix which is coated with a mucus layer.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] This layer of mucus can slow down the passage of sperm and can result in many sperm perishing before they can enter the uterus.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Donor sperm is sometimes tested for mucus penetration if it is to be used for ICI inseminations but partner sperm may or may not be able to pass through the cervix.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In these cases, the use of IUI can provide a more efficient delivery of the sperm.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In general terms, IUI is usually regarded as more efficient than ICI or IVI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It is therefore the method of choice for single and lesbian women wishing to conceive using donor sperm since this group of recipients usually require artificial insemination because they do not have a male partner, not because they have medical problems.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Owing to the high number of these recipients using donor sperm services, IUI is therefore the most popular method of insemination today at a fertility clinic.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The term 'artificial insemination' has, in many cases, come to mean IUI insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It is important that washed sperm is used because unwashed sperm may elicit uterine cramping, expelling the semen and causing pain, due to content of prostaglandins.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] (Prostaglandins are also the compounds responsible for causing the myometrium to contract and expel the menses from the uterus, during menstruation.) Resting on the table for fifteen minutes after an IUI is optimal for the woman to increase the pregnancy rate.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Using this technique, as with ICI, fertilization takes place naturally in the external part of the fallopian tubes in the same way that occurs following intercourse.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] For heterosexual couples, the indications to perform an intrauterine insemination are usually a moderate male factor, the incapability to ejaculate in vagina and an idiopathic infertility.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A short period of ejaculatory abstinence before intrauterine insemination is associated with higher pregnancy rates.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] For the man, a TMS of more than 5 million per ml is optimal.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Lesbians and single women are less likely to have fertility issues of their own and enabling donor sperm to be inserted directly into the womb will often produce a better chance of conceiving.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A 2019 showed that pregnancy rates were similar between lesbian women and heterosexual women undergoing IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, it was found that there is a significantly higher multiple gestation rate among lesbian women undergoing ovulation induction (OI) when compared to lesbian women undergoing natural cycles.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Unlike ICI, intrauterine insemination normally requires a medical practitioner to perform the procedure.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] One of the requirements is to have at least one permeable tube, proved by hysterosalpingography.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The infertility duration is also important.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A female under 30 years of age has optimal chances with IUI; A promising cycle is one that offers two follicles measuring more than 16 mm, and estrogen of more than 500 pg/mL on the day of hCG administration.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, GnRH agonist administration at the time of implantation does not improve pregnancy outcome in intrauterine insemination cycles according to a randomized controlled trial.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The cost breakdown for Intrauterine Insemination (IUI) involves several components.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The procedure itself typically ranges from $300 to $1,000 per cycle without insurance.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The cost of the sperm may vary widely, with prices per vial ranging from $500 to $1,000 or more from a sperm bank.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Additional expenses might include consultation fees, ovulation-inducing medication, ultrasounds, and blood tests.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The extent of insurance coverage for fertility treatments, including Intrauterine Insemination (IUI), varies considerably.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Some insurance plans may cover some of the costs, while others may not provide any financial support for fertility treatments.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Coverage depends on various factors, such as the insurance plan, state policies and regulations, and the underlying cause of infertility.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Several states have mandated insurers to provide coverage for infertility services.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] IUI can be used in conjunction with controlled ovarian hyperstimulation (COH).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Clomiphene Citrate is the first line, Letrozole is second line, in order to stimulate ovaries before moving on to IVF.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Still, advanced maternal age causes decreased success rates; women aged 38–39 years appear to have reasonable success during the first two cycles of ovarian hyperstimulation and IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, for women aged over 40 years, there appears to be no benefit after a single cycle of COH/IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Medical experts therefore recommend considering in vitro fertilization after one failed COH/IUI cycle for women aged over 40 years.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A double intrauterine insemination theoretically increases pregnancy rates by decreasing the risk of missing the fertile window during ovulation.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, a randomized trial of insemination after ovarian hyperstimulation found no difference in live birth rate between single and double intrauterine insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A Cochrane found uncertain evidence about the effect of IUI compared with timed intercourse or expectant management on live birth rates but IUI with controlled ovarian hyperstimulation is probably better than expectant management.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Due to the lack of reliable evidence from controlled clinical trials, it is not certain which semen preparation techniques are more effective (wash and centrifugation; swim-up; or gradient) in terms of pregnancy and live birth rates.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Intrauterine insemination (IUI) procedures have shown to be more successful and effective with certain factors taken into account.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] One major factor is the health of the sperm that is used.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Sperm motility, which is improved by the sperm washing procedure, sperm density, and the sperm concentration index, all of which are found through washing and studying of the health of the specimen, are major indicators of a positive pregnancy test following IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The age of both the male and female (egg and sperm donors) involved in the process are extremely important.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Although age has typically been pinned on the women as a determining factor, research shows that both male and female age has about equal impact on the success of the procedure.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Along with age, the duration of fertility is also found to be a factor in IUI success, the longer one faces infertility, the lower the chance of a positive pregnancy test occurring.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] When people talk about age as a risk factor, they are generally speaking to the way in which the DNA in the eggs and sperm have increased probabilities of mutations.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Lastly, the biological factors of the female's body can have some impact on the success of the IUI procedure.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The endometrial thickness at time of insemination is moderately important, though less of a concern than some of the other factors.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The number of follicles developed, grown, and retrieved from the ovaries during ovarian stimulation is particularly important and a major success factor in fertility treatments.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] And lastly, for the female partner, the estradiol concentration within the body on the day of HCG administration.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Because IUI is less expensive and less invasive than other fertility options (for example, in vitro fertilisation, or IVF), it is typically the first outlet for those looking for fertility treatments.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] For individuals or couples who struggle with getting pregnant, but haven't explored any fertility treatments yet, they would be good candidates for IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] IUI provides those with a more affordable and accessible outlet for fertility treatments, however, IUI may not be the most successful option if it is determined to be female factor infertility.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] IUI is also a very good option for single individuals who are using donor sperm, as donor sperm undergoes regulations and checks which may not be the case for a partner sperm donation.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] IUI can additionally be a good fertility outlet for lesbian or queer couples as they most often do not face infertility, and would most likely be using regulated and checked donor sperm.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Furthermore, surrogates can be artificially inseminated through IUI to help other individuals and/or couples become pregnant with their sperm.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Intrauterine tuboperitoneal insemination (IUTPI) involves injection of washed sperm into both the uterus and fallopian tubes.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The cervix is then clamped to prevent leakage to the vagina, best achieved with a specially designed double nut bivalve (DNB) speculum.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The sperm is mixed to create a volume of 10 ml, sufficient to fill the uterine cavity, pass through the interstitial part of the tubes and the ampulla, finally reaching the peritoneal cavity and the Pouch of Douglas where it would be mixed with the peritoneal and follicular fluid.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] IUTPI can be useful in unexplained infertility, mild or moderate male infertility, and mild or moderate endometriosis.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In non-tubal sub fertility, fallopian tube sperm perfusion may be the preferred technique over intrauterine insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Intratubal insemination (ITI) involves injection of washed sperm into the fallopian tube, although this procedure is no longer generally regarded as having any beneficial effect compared with IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] ITI however, should not be confused with gamete intrafallopian transfer, where both eggs and sperm are mixed outside the woman's body and then immediately inserted into the fallopian tube where fertilization takes place.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Although many fertilization procedures, like IUI are typically carried out in a medical setting, society is increasingly recognizing the important role that this plays in the lives of individuals who might otherwise not conceive through heterosexual penetrative sexual intercourse.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination using a sperm donor for LGBTQ+ individuals and couples is one of the more cost-effective avenues to parenting.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Indeed, in the early days, there were very few fertility clinics which would provide services to single women and lesbian couples.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Most donor insemination procedures undertaken in many countries today are for lesbian couples or single mainly lesbian women, yet much of their rhetoric and advertising is directed at heterosexual couples.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Indeed, many sperm banks seem reluctant to inform donors that most of their donations will be used for lesbians and single women.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] To improve the way society talks about and carries out donor insemination inclusive language may be used.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] One way to do this is to bring LGBTQ narratives into this process, with a particular emphasis on this being a family-centered process.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Even in a medical setting, it is important to bring intimacy and family-centeredness into this process, as this promotes connectedness and inclusiveness in what can be seen as a hostile and discriminatory environment.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Lesbian couples may either select a friend or family member as their sperm donor or choose an anonymous donor.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] After a sperm donor is selected, a couple can proceed with donor sperm IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] IUI is an economic option for same-sex couples and can be done without the use of medication.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] According to a study from 2021, lesbian women undergoing IUI had an average clinical pregnancy rate of 13.2% per cycle and 42.2% success rate giving the average number of cycles at 3.6.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The rates of successful pregnancy for artificial insemination are 10-15% per menstrual cycle using ICI, and 15–20% per cycle for IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In IUI, about 60 to 70% have achieved pregnancy after 6 cycles.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, these pregnancy rates may be very misleading, since many factors have to be included to give a meaningful answer, e.g. definition of success and calculation of the total population.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] These rates can be influenced by age, overall reproductive health, and if the patient had an orgasm during the insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The literature is conflicting on immobilization after insemination has increasing the chances of pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Previous data suggests that it is statistically significant for the patient to remain immobile for 15 minutes after insemination, while another review article claims that it is not.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] A point of consideration, is that it does cost the patient or healthcare system to remain immobile for 15 minutes if it does increase the chances.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] For couples with unexplained infertility, unstimulated IUI is no more effective than natural means of conception.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The pregnancy rate also depends on the total sperm count, or, more specifically, the total motile sperm count (TMSC), used in a cycle.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The success rate increases with increasing TMSC, but only up to a certain count, when other factors become limiting to success.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The summed pregnancy rate of two cycles using a TMSC of 5 million (may be a TSC of ~10 million on graph) in each cycle is substantially higher than one single cycle using a TMSC of 10 million.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, although more cost-efficient, using a lower TMSC also increases the average time taken to achieve pregnancy.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Women whose age is becoming a major factor in fertility may not want to spend that extra time.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The number of samples (ejaculates) required to give rise to a child varies substantially from person to person, as well as from clinic to clinic.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The pregnancy rate increases with increasing number of motile sperm used, but only up to a certain degree, when other factors become limiting instead.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] With these numbers, one sample would on average help giving rise to 0.1–0.6 children, that is, it actually takes on average 2–5 samples to make a child.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] is the fraction of the volume that remains after centrifugation of the sample, which may be about half (0.5) to a third (0.33).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Thus, only 1–3 samples may be needed for a child if used for IUI.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] One of the key issues arising from the rise of dependency on assisted reproductive technology (ARTs) is the pressure placed on couples to conceive, "where children are highly desired, parenthood is culturally mandatory, and childlessness socially unacceptable".
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The medicalization of infertility creates a framework in which individuals are encouraged to think of infertility quite negatively.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In many cultures donor insemination is religiously and culturally prohibited, often meaning that less accessible "high tech" and expensive ARTs, like IVF, are the only solution.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] If good records are not kept, the offspring when grown up risk accidental incest.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The risk factors of artificial insemination are comparatively low to other forms of fertility treatment.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The most prominent risk factor would be infection after the procedure, with other risk factors including a higher risk of having twins or triplets, and minor vaginal bleeding during the procedure.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Although these risk factors are minor and generally manageable, there is a significant knowledge gap between identity groups around risk factors for fertility treatments in general.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The implications of this knowledge gap between LGTBQ+ individuals and their heterosexual counterparts are serious and worth noting.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Lack of access to proper information and risk factors around procedures like these may dissuade someone from pursuing these procedures altogether.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] As a result, there will be less normalization of LGBTQ+ family making and reproduction, which only perpetuates this cycle of lack of information among LGBTQ+ folks.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Some countries restrict artificial insemination in a variety of ways.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] For example, some countries do not permit AI for single women, and other countries do not permit the use of donor sperm.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination used to be seen as adultery and was illegal until the 1960s when states started recognizing the child born from artificial insemination as legitimate.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Once the children began to be recognized as legitimate, legal questions around who the parents of the child are, how to handle surrogacy, paternity rights, and eventually artificial insemination and LGBT+ parents began to arise.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Prior to the use of artificial insemination, the legal parents of a child were the two people who conceived the child or the person who birthed the child and their legal spouse, but artificial insemination complicates the legal process of becoming a parent as well as who is the parent of the child.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Deciding who the parents of the child are is the largest legal predicament around artificial insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, questions around surrogacy and donor's rights also appear as a side question to determining the parent(s).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] When children are conceived the traditional way, there is little discrepancy around who the legal parents of the child are.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, because children conceived using artificial insemination may not be genetically related to one or more of their parents, who the legal parents of the child are can come into question.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Prior to the passage of the Uniform Parentage Act in 1973, children conceived via artificial insemination were deemed as "illegitimate" children.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The Uniform Parentage Act then recognized the children born from artificial insemination as legal and laid precedent for how the legal parents of the child were decided.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] However, this act applied only to the children of those married couples.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It established that the person who birthed the child was the mother and the father would be the husband of the woman.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In 2002, the Uniform Parentage Act, which is adopted individually on a state by state basis, was revised to address non married couples and states that an unmarried couple has the same rights to the child that a married couple would.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] This extended who has the right to be a parent to a man who would supposedly fill in the social role as a "father." There were now numerous ways to establish parental rights for both the mother and the father depending on if the child was born using a sperm donor or a surrogate.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Currently, a revised version of the Uniform Parentage Act is starting to be passed in a few states that expands how parental relations can be determined.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] This bill includes expanding "father" to mean any person who would fill the role of a father, regardless of their gender and "mother" is expanded to anyone who gives birth to the child regardless of gender.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] There is no federal law that applies to all fifty states when it comes to artificial insemination and paternity rights, but the Uniform Parentage Act is a model which many states have adopted.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Under the 1973 UPA, married heterosexual couples making use of artificial insemination through a licensed physician could list the husband as the natural father of the child, rather than the sperm donor.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Generally paternity is not an issue when artificial insemination is between a married woman and an anonymous donor.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Most states provide that anonymous donors' paternity claims are not recognized, and most sperm donation centers make use of contracts that require donors to sign away their paternity rights before they can participate.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] When the mother knows the donor, however, or engages in artificial insemination while unmarried, complications may arise.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] When one or a number of these things is true, courts have at times found written agreements relinquishing parental rights to be unenforceable.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Some theologically buttressed arguments reject the moral validity of this practice, such as Pope John XXIII.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] There are critics of artificial insemination who voice concerns regarding the potential for AI to encourage eugenicist practices through selection of particular traits.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The line of reasoning follows the history of artificial insemination in breeding livestock and other domesticated animals wherein preferred traits are encouraged through human-controlled selection.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination is used for pets, livestock, endangered species, and animals in zoos or marine parks difficult to transport.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination is much more common than natural mating, as it allows several female animals to be impregnated from a single male.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] For instance, up to 30-40 female pigs can be impregnated from a single boar.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Workers collect the semen by masturbating the boars, then insert it into the sows via a raised catheter known as a pork stork.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Boars are still physically used to excite the females prior to insemination, but are prevented from actually mating.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Semen is collected, extended, then cooled or frozen.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It can be used on-site or shipped to the female's location.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] If frozen, the small plastic tube holding the semen is referred to as a *straw*.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] To allow the sperm to remain viable during the time before and after it is frozen, the semen is mixed with a solution containing glycerol or other cryoprotectants.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] An *extender* is a solution that allows the semen from a donor to impregnate more females by making insemination possible with fewer sperm.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Antibiotics, such as streptomycin, are sometimes added to the sperm to control some bacterial venereal diseases.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Before the actual insemination, estrus may be induced through the use of progestogen and another hormone (usually PMSG or Prostaglandin F2α).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The first viviparous animal to be artificially fertilized was a dog.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The experiment was conducted with success by the Italian Lazzaro Spallanzani in 1780.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Another pioneer was the Russian Ilya Ivanov in 1899.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In 1935, diluted semen from Suffolk sheep was flown from Cambridge in Britain to Kraków, Poland, as part of an international research project.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The participants included Prawochenki (Poland), Milovanoff (USSR), Hammond and Walton (UK), and Thomasset (Uruguay).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Modern artificial insemination was pioneered by John O.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Almquist of Pennsylvania State University.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] He improved breeding efficiency by the use of antibiotics (first proven with penicillin in 1946) to control bacterial growth, decreasing embryonic mortality, and increase fertility.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] This, and various new techniques for processing, freezing, and thawing of frozen semen significantly enhanced the practical utilization of artificial insemination in the livestock industry and earned him the 1981 Wolf Foundation Prize in Agriculture.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Many techniques developed by him have since been applied to other species, including humans.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination is used in many non-human animals, including sheep, horses, cattle, pigs, dogs, pedigree animals generally, zoo animals, turkeys and creatures as tiny as honeybees and as massive as orcas (killer whales).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination of farm animals is common in the developed world, especially for breeding dairy cattle (75% of all inseminations).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Swine are also bred using this method (up to 85% of all inseminations).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] It is an economical means for a livestock breeder to improve their herds utilizing males having desirable traits.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Although common with cattle and swine, artificial insemination is not as widely practiced in the breeding of horses.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] In modern species conservation, semen collection and artificial insemination are used also in birds.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Scientists working with captive orcas were able to pioneer the technique in the early 2000s, resulting in "the first successful conceptions, resulting in live offspring, using artificial insemination in any cetacean species".
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] John Hargrove, a SeaWorld trainer, describes Kasatka as being the first orca to receive artificial insemination.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination on animals has been criticised as a violation of animal rights, with animal rights advocates equating it with rape and arguing it constitutes institutionalized bestiality.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Artificial insemination of farm animals is condemned by animal rights campaigners such as People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA) and Joey Carbstrong, who identify the practice as a form of rape due to its sexual, involuntary and perceived painful nature.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Animal rights organizations such as PETA and Mercy for Animals frequently write against the practice in their articles.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Much of the meat production in the United States depends on artificial insemination, resulting in an explosive growth of the procedure over the past three decades.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The state of Kansas makes no exceptions for artificial insemination under its bestiality law, thus making the procedure illegal.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Both spouses or the unmarried woman must consent in advance to artificial insemination or embryo transfer.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The parenting project must be validated through a series of interviews with professionals (doctors, psychologists, etc.).
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] Individuals benefiting from artificial insemination must be of reproductive age.
[src:artificial-insemination/artificial-insemination] The 2021 Bioethics Law has expanded the scope of Medically Assisted Procreation (MAP).
